[1] Cholera - Uganda (Kasese district)
Date: Mon 2 Oct 2017
Source: Daily Monitor [edited]
http://goo.gl/iczGSf


A cholera outbreak that hit Kasese district last week [week of 25 Sep 2017] has so far claimed 3 lives with more than 80 admitted, medics say. Dr Alphose Gatare, the Bwera general hospital medical superintendent says the 3 died on Sun 1 Oct 2017. "Yesterday [1 Oct 2017] we lost 3 people. 2 died on arrival and the other one had already been put on treatment. It is unfortunate that we lost them after reaching hospital," Dr Gatare said. He says those who died were brought to the hospital after being dehydrated something that made it difficult for the doctors to find the veins to apply medication. The most affected villages are Katholhu in Nyakiyumbu sub county and Bunyiswa in Bwera sub county, about 10 km [6.2 mi] from the hospital.

Dr Gatare says the hospital has been struggling with supplies because they had not yet received cholera drugs from the National Medical Stores [NMS]. Bwera hospital which is about 5 km [3.1 mi] from the border with Democratic Republic of Congo [DRC] has been relying on supplies from Kagando hospital in Kisinga sub county, the doctor revealed. "We have asked NMS to send supplies immediately because it may not be easy for us if more are admitted. Kagando hospital and Medecins Sans Frontieres have been assisting us in the past week," Dr Gatare said.

Cholera has been persistent in sub counties bordering DRC with an outbreak at least every year. Sometimes, the epidemic spreads across the border forcing an influx of patients from the DRC to Bwera hospital.

[Byline: Misairi Thembo Kahungu]

